{"title_page": "Andr\u00e9 Brasil", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n|name = Andr\u00e9 Brasil\n|image =Andr\u00e9 Brasi 2012cr.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|caption =Andr\u00e9 Brasi in 2012\n|fullname = Andr\u00e9 Brasil Esteves\n|nicknames =\n|nationality = \n|birth_date ={{birth date and age|1984|5|23}}\n|birth_place = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil<ref name=bio>[http://www.andrebrasil.com/site/biografia Biographia]. andrebrasil.com</ref>\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|height=183 cm<ref name=bio/>\n|weight=75 kg\n|strokes = [[Backstroke]], [[butterfly stroke|butterfly]], [[Freestyle swimming|freestyle]], [[Medley swimming|medley]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|50 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2008 Beijing|100 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2008 Beijing|400 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2008 Beijing|100 m butterfly S10}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|50 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2012 London|100 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|2012 London}}|100 m butterfly S10}}\n{{MedalSilver|2008 Beijing|{{nowrap|200 m Individual Medley SM10}}}}\n{{MedalSilver|2012 London|200 m Individual Medley SM10}}\n{{MedalSilver|2012 London|100 m backstroke S10}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle S10|100 m freestyle S10]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay 34pts|4\u00d7100 m freestyle relay 34pts]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly S10|100 m butterfly S10]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay 34pts|4\u00d7100 m medley relay 34pts]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Swimming World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]] S10}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]] S10}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]] S10}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]] | [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|100&nbsp;m freestyle relay 34pts]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Swimming World Championships|IPC World Championships 25m]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 IPC Swimming World Championships 25 m|2009 Rio de Janeiro]]|50 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|400 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m backstroke S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m butterfly S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m individual medley SM10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|200 m individual medley SM10}}\n{{MedalSilver|2009 Rio de Janeiro|4\u00d750 m medley relay 20 pts}}\n}}\n\n'''Andre Brasil''' (born May 23, 1984) is a Paralympic swimmer from [[Brazil]]. He had [[poliomyelitis]] as a child.<ref>[http://www.cidadeolimpica.com/en/brazilian-athletes-gather-five-years-before-the-rio-de-janeiro-paralympic-games/ Brazilian athletes gather five years before the Rio de Janeiro Paralympic Games]. cidadeolimpica.com {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130215173257/http://www.cidadeolimpica.com/en/brazilian-athletes-gather-five-years-before-the-rio-de-janeiro-paralympic-games/ |date=2013-02-15 }}</ref> He competes in the [[S10 (classification)|S10]] classification.\n\nHe won gold for [[Brazil at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]. He also broke S10 world records in three events, and a Paralympic record in a fourth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/18966.asp?q=Paralympics,%20Swimming:%20World%20Records%20Continue%20to%20Fall|title=Paralympics, Swimming: World Records Continue to Fall|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=September 9, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213175215/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/18966.asp?q=Paralympics,%20Swimming:%20World%20Records%20Continue%20to%20Fall|archive-date=2012-02-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2008PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=100+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=Beijing 2008 Paralympic Games - Swimming - Men's 100 m Freestyle S10|publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]]|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2008PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=50+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=Beijing 2008 Paralympic Games - Swimming - Men's 50 m Freestyle S10|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2008PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=400+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=Beijing 2008 Paralympic Games - Swimming - Men's 400 m Freestyle S10|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> He is unbeaten in the men's 400 m freestyle S10 event.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} He then went on to win and break a world record at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in 50 m freestyle S10, with a time of 23.16 seconds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2012PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=50+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=London 2012 - Paralympic Games Swimming - Men's 50 m Freestyle S10|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> beating his old record of 23.44 seconds.\n\n{{As of|February 2013}}, he is [[List of IPC world records in swimming|S10 world record holder]] in [[long course]] 50, 100 and 200 metre freestyle, 50 and 100 metre butterfly and 50 metre backstroke events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/sdms/web/sw/record.pdf.sw.php?xml=0&rct=RCTWR&dis=LC&gen=M&evt= |title=IPC Swimming World Records - Long Course |publisher=International Paralympic Committee |accessdate=February 3, 2013 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andr\u00e9 Brasil}}\n* {{IPC athlete|id=andre-brasil|old_id=681126|name=Andre Brasil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brasil, Andre}}\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers of Brazil]]\n[[Category:People with polio]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:World record holders in paralympic swimming]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:S10-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-swimming-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n|name = Andr\u00e9 Brasil\n|image =Andr\u00e9 Brasi 2012cr.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|caption =Andr\u00e9 Brasi in 2012\n|fullname = Andr\u00e9 Brasil Esteves\n|nicknames =\n|nationality = \n|birth_date ={{birth date and age|1984|5|23}}\n|birth_place = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil<ref name=bio>[http://www.andrebrasil.com/site/biografia Biographia]. andrebrasil.com</ref>\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|height=183 cm<ref name=bio/>\n|weight=75 kg\n|strokes = [[Backstroke]], [[butterfly stroke|butterfly]], [[Freestyle swimming|freestyle]], [[Medley swimming|medley]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|50 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2008 Beijing|100 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2008 Beijing|400 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2008 Beijing|100 m butterfly S10}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|50 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2012 London|100 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|2012 London}}|100 m butterfly S10}}\n{{MedalSilver|2008 Beijing|{{nowrap|200 m Individual Medley SM10}}}}\n{{MedalSilver|2012 London|200 m Individual Medley SM10}}\n{{MedalSilver|2012 London|100 m backstroke S10}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle S10|100 m freestyle S10]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay 34pts|4\u00d7100 m freestyle relay 34pts]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly S10|100 m butterfly S10]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay 34pts|4\u00d7100 m medley relay 34pts]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Swimming World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]] S10}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]] S10}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]] S10}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]] | [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|100&nbsp;m freestyle relay 34pts]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Swimming World Championships|IPC World Championships 25m]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 IPC Swimming World Championships 25 m|2009 Rio de Janeiro]]|50 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|400 m freestyle S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m backstroke S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m butterfly S10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|100 m individual medley SM10}}\n{{MedalGold|2009 Rio de Janeiro|200 m individual medley SM10}}\n{{MedalSilver|2009 Rio de Janeiro|4\u00d750 m medley relay 20 pts}}\n}}\n\n'''Andre Brasil''' (born May 23, 1984) is a Paralympic swimmer from [[Brazil]]. He had [[poliomyelitis]] as a child.<ref>[http://www.cidadeolimpica.com/en/brazilian-athletes-gather-five-years-before-the-rio-de-janeiro-paralympic-games/ Brazilian athletes gather five years before the Rio de Janeiro Paralympic Games]. cidadeolimpica.com {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130215173257/http://www.cidadeolimpica.com/en/brazilian-athletes-gather-five-years-before-the-rio-de-janeiro-paralympic-games/ |date=2013-02-15 }}</ref> He competes in the [[S10 (classification)|S10]] classification.\n\nHe won gold for [[Brazil at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]. He also broke S10 world records in three events, and a Paralympic record in a fourth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/18966.asp?q=Paralympics,%20Swimming:%20World%20Records%20Continue%20to%20Fall|title=Paralympics, Swimming: World Records Continue to Fall|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=September 9, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213175215/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/18966.asp?q=Paralympics,%20Swimming:%20World%20Records%20Continue%20to%20Fall|archive-date=2012-02-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2008PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=100+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=Beijing 2008 Paralympic Games - Swimming - Men's 100 m Freestyle S10|publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]]|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2008PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=50+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=Beijing 2008 Paralympic Games - Swimming - Men's 50 m Freestyle S10|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2008PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=400+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=Beijing 2008 Paralympic Games - Swimming - Men's 400 m Freestyle S10|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> He is unbeaten in the men's 400 m freestyle S10 event.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} He then went on to win and break a world record at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in 50 m freestyle S10, with a time of 23.16 seconds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=swimming&competition=2012PG&gender=m&discipline=&event=50+m+Freestyle&eclass=S10|title=London 2012 - Paralympic Games Swimming - Men's 50 m Freestyle S10|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=September 9, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> beating his old record of 23.44 seconds.\n\n{{As of|February 2013}}, he is [[List of IPC world records in swimming|S10 world record holder]] in [[long course]] 50, 100 and 200 metre freestyle, 50 and 100 metre butterfly and 50 metre backstroke events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/sdms/web/sw/record.pdf.sw.php?xml=0&rct=RCTWR&dis=LC&gen=M&evt= |title=IPC Swimming World Records - Long Course |publisher=International Paralympic Committee |accessdate=February 3, 2013 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andr\u00e9 Brasil}}\n* {{IPC athlete|681126|Andr\u00e9 Brasil Esteves}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brasil, Andre}}\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers of Brazil]]\n[[Category:People with polio]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:World record holders in paralympic swimming]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:S10-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-swimming-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Brasil"}
{"title_page": "MotorWeek", "text_new": " \n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = MotorWeek\n| image                = MotorWeek logo.png\n| caption              = MotorWeek Logo\n| genre                = [[Automotive]]\n| creator              = [[John H. Davis (television)|John H. Davis]]\n| starring             = [[John H. Davis (television)|John H. Davis]]<br>[[Pat Goss]]<br>[[Yolanda Vazquez (television)|Yolanda Vazquez]]<br>[[Zach Maskell]]<br>Joyce Braga (past)<br>Elizabeth A. Nardone (past)<br>Charlotte Nichols (past)<br>[[Craig Singhaus]] (past)<br>[[Lisa Barrow]] (past)<br>[[Jennifer Khasnabis]] (past)<br>Anquionette Crosby (past)<br>[[Jessica Choksey]] (past)<br>Henry Kopacz (past)\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 39\n| num_episodes         = 1,000\n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = [[John H. Davis (television)|John H. Davis]]\n| location             = [[Owings Mills, Maryland]]\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| network              = [[Maryland Public Television]] ([[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]])\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] [[SDTV]] (1981-2009; seasons 1-28)<br/>[[1080i]] [[HDTV]] (2009-present; seasons 29-present)\n| audio_format         = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1981|10|15}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = http://www.motorweek.org/\n}}\n'''''MotorWeek''''' is an American half-hour automotive television series. The program premiered on October 15, 1981 and was hosted by automotive journalist John H. Davis, who is also the series\u2019 creator and executive producer.<ref name=who>{{cite web|title=Who's Who|url=http://www.motorweek.org/about/whos_who/|website=MotorWeek|publisher=Maryland Public Television|accessdate=23 January 2016}}</ref> ''MotorWeek'' is produced by [[Maryland Public Television]] and is seen nationwide on [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS), [[V-me]] and internationally on the [[American Forces Network]].\n\nThe half-hour program is presented in a magazine style format, with reviews, comparisons, news, and features. ''MotorWeek'''s first slogan was \"Television's automotive magazine\" from 1981 to 1995, and was changed to \"Television's original automotive magazine\" in Season 15 (1995-1996), although the BBC's ''[[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' debuted in 1977.\n\n==Syndication==\nOn September 11, 1993, during the premiere of Season 13 (1993-1994), ''MotorWeek'' began syndicating to local stations, and was first syndicated by [[ITC Entertainment]] from 1993 to 1998. It has also aired on [[Speedvision]], [[Speed Channel]], [[Motor Trend (TV channel)|Velocity]], [[Motor Trend (TV channel)|Velocity by Discovery]], the Spanish-language network [[V-me]], and [[Motor Trend (TV channel)|Motor Trend]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nEach year, MotorWeek puts more than 150 new cars, trucks, and SUVs to the test, providing consumer-oriented vehicle reviews. Its video Road Test segments focus on performance, technology, practicality and dollar value, and feature ''MotorWeek'''s exclusive energy efficient rating system which compares each vehicle\u2019s fuel economy to the best-rated vehicle in its class. The ''MotorWeek'' team includes master technician [[Pat Goss]] who brings viewers practical advice for keeping cars on the road and out of the shop. Reporters present timely reports on consumer trends, safety issues and the environment, along with innovative, offbeat stories on the automotive world gone extreme. Beginning in 1983, ''MotorWeek'' launched its [[MotorWeek Drivers\u2019 Choice Awards|Drivers\u2019 Choice Awards]] which are among the auto industry\u2019s most prestigious honors. The Drivers\u2019 Choice Awards are unique for their consumer focus and represent the definitive list of best automotive picks in the most popular vehicle categories, including the coveted  \u201cBest of the Year\u201d award. They are presented annually during the [[Chicago Auto Show]]. Beginning in season 29 (2009-2010), ''MotorWeek'' began broadcasting in [[widescreen]] [[1080i]] [[HDTV]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{empty section|date=February 2020}}\nMotorWeek did a Retro Review Marathon. They started on April 2, 2020 with Season 4, until May 3, 2020 with Season 7b.<ref name=marathon>{{cite web|title=MotorWeek Retro Review Marathon|url=https://www.youtube.com/post/UgxQAehCsH0Ry3JGQ6x4AaABCQ|website=YouTube|publisher=Maryland Public Television}}</ref>\n\n==Segments==\n*Road Test: Featuring a road test of new vehicles.\n*Goss' Garage: Pat Goss would teach viewers on how to keep automobiles in good repair.\n*Quick Spin: Take a quick spin on new vehicles.\n*Two Wheelin': A two wheel review on [[motorcycle]]s.\n*First Drive: A first look at new vehicles.\n*Muscle Car Memories: A wide variety of vintage, classic, and memorable muscle cars.\n*Behind The Wall: The ''MotorWeek'' staff takes behind the wall for their high speed driving skills.\n*Car of the Week: Featuring a photo album of automobiles sent in by viewers.\n*Stomp, Stay, and Steer: John Davis teaches viewers on how to stomp, stay, and steer.\n*A Quick Look: Featuring a quick look at new vehicles.\n*Long Term Test Update: News on cars loaned to ''MotorWeek'' for tests.\n*MotorNews: An in-depth report on new vehicles.\n*What's New on Wheels: A close look at new products on the automotive scene.\n*Over The Edge: An automotive industry on overdrive.\n*FYI: Featuring an in-depth report on consumer trending.\n*Retro Review: A look back at ''MotorWeek'' reviews from past seasons.\n*Eye Spy: Featuring photographic closeups of automobiles.\n*Taking the High Road: Featuring automobiles from the past and present.\n\n==Theme music==\nFrom the show's premiere in 1981 until 1987, ''MotorWeek'''s original theme music was composed by Don Barto. Beginning with the 1987-88 season, Mark Roumelis took over as music composer.\n\n==Sets==\nDuring the first six seasons of ''MotorWeek'', the set looks like a styling studio with cars, drafting tools, and paraphernalia on the wall was used from 1981 to 1987. Beginning with the 1987-88 season, ''MotorWeek'' began taping outdoors rather than in a studio.\n\n==Track==\nFrom 1981 to present day, ''MotorWeek'' has been use the 75-80 Dragway.<ref name=dragway>{{cite web|title=MotorWeek Over The Edge:75-80 Dragway|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9wHC7LwT0U|website=YouTube|publisher=Maryland Public Television}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.motorweek.org/ MotorWeek home page]\n* {{IMDb title|0244912|MotorWeek}}\n\n{{PBSTV}}\n\n[[Category:Automotive television series]]\n[[Category:PBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITC Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:1981 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": " \n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = MotorWeek\n| image                = MotorWeek logo.png\n| caption              = MotorWeek Logo\n| genre                = [[Automotive]]\n| creator              = [[John H. Davis (television)|John H. Davis]]\n| starring             = [[John H. Davis (television)|John H. Davis]]<br>[[Pat Goss]]<br>[[Yolanda Vazquez (television)|Yolanda Vazquez]]<br>[[Zach Maskell]]<br>Joyce Braga (past)<br>Elizabeth A. Nardone (past)<br>Charlotte Nichols (past)<br>[[Craig Singhaus]] (past)<br>[[Lisa Barrow]] (past)<br>[[Jennifer Khasnabis]] (past)<br>Anquionette Crosby (past)<br>[[Jessica Choksey]] (past)<br>Henry Kopacz (past)\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 39\n| num_episodes         = 1,000\n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = [[John H. Davis (television)|John H. Davis]]\n| location             = [[Owings Mills, Maryland]]\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| network              = [[Maryland Public Television]] ([[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]])\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] [[SDTV]] (1981-2009; seasons 1-28)<br/>[[1080i]] [[HDTV]] (2009-present; seasons 29-present)\n| audio_format         = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1981|10|15}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = http://www.motorweek.org/\n}}\n'''''MotorWeek''''' is an American half-hour automotive television series. The program premiered on October 15, 1981 and was hosted by automotive journalist John H. Davis, who is also the series\u2019 creator and executive producer.<ref name=who>{{cite web|title=Who's Who|url=http://www.motorweek.org/about/whos_who/|website=MotorWeek|publisher=Maryland Public Television|accessdate=23 January 2016}}</ref> ''MotorWeek'' is produced by [[Maryland Public Television]] and is seen nationwide on [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS), [[V-me]] and internationally on the [[American Forces Network]].\n\nThe half-hour program is presented in a magazine style format, with reviews, comparisons, news, and features. ''MotorWeek'''s first slogan was \"Television's automotive magazine\" from 1981 to 1995, and was changed to \"Television's original automotive magazine\" in Season 15 (1995-1996), although the BBC's ''[[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' debuted in 1977.\n\n==Syndication==\nOn September 11, 1993, during the premiere of Season 13 (1993-1994), ''MotorWeek'' began syndicating to local stations, and was first syndicated by [[ITC Entertainment]] from 1993 to 1998. It has also aired on [[Speedvision]], [[Speed Channel]], [[Motor Trend (TV channel)|Velocity]], [[Motor Trend (TV channel)|Velocity by Discovery]], the Spanish-language network [[V-me]], and [[Motor Trend (TV channel)|Motor Trend]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nEach year, MotorWeek puts more than 150 new cars, trucks, and SUVs to the test, providing consumer-oriented vehicle reviews. Its video Road Test segments focus on performance, technology, practicality and dollar value, and feature ''MotorWeek'''s exclusive energy efficient rating system which compares each vehicle\u2019s fuel economy to the best-rated vehicle in its class. The ''MotorWeek'' team includes master technician [[Pat Goss]] who brings viewers practical advice for keeping cars on the road and out of the shop. Reporters present timely reports on consumer trends, safety issues and the environment, along with innovative, offbeat stories on the automotive world gone extreme. Beginning in 1983, ''MotorWeek'' launched its [[MotorWeek Drivers\u2019 Choice Awards|Drivers\u2019 Choice Awards]] which are among the auto industry\u2019s most prestigious honors. The Drivers\u2019 Choice Awards are unique for their consumer focus and represent the definitive list of best automotive picks in the most popular vehicle categories, including the coveted  \u201cBest of the Year\u201d award. They are presented annually during the [[Chicago Auto Show]]. Beginning in season 29 (2009-2010), ''MotorWeek'' began broadcasting in [[widescreen]] [[1080i]] [[HDTV]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{empty section|date=February 2020}}\nMotorWeek did a Retro Review Marathon. They started on April 2, 2020 with Season 4, until May 3, 2020 with Season 7b.<ref name=marathon>{{cite web|title=MotorWeek Retro Review Marathon|url=https://www.youtube.com/post/UgxQAehCsH0Ry3JGQ6x4AaABCQ|website=YouTube|publisher=Maryland Public Television}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2, 2020, MotorWeek live streamed Season 4 due to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=season4>{{cite web|title=MotorWeek Season Four 1984-1985|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4ajqYKe9xL4|website=YouTube|publisher=Maryland Public Television}}</ref>\n\n==Segments==\n*Road Test: Featuring a road test of new vehicles.\n*Goss' Garage: Pat Goss would teach viewers on how to keep automobiles in good repair.\n*Quick Spin: Take a quick spin on new vehicles.\n*Two Wheelin': A two wheel review on [[motorcycle]]s.\n*First Drive: A first look at new vehicles.\n*Muscle Car Memories: A wide variety of vintage, classic, and memorable muscle cars.\n*Behind The Wall: The ''MotorWeek'' staff takes behind the wall for their high speed driving skills.\n*Car of the Week: Featuring a photo album of automobiles sent in by viewers.\n*Stomp, Stay, and Steer: John Davis teaches viewers on how to stomp, stay, and steer.\n*A Quick Look: Featuring a quick look at new vehicles.\n*Long Term Test Update: News on cars loaned to ''MotorWeek'' for tests.\n*MotorNews: An in-depth report on new vehicles.\n*What's New on Wheels: A close look at new products on the automotive scene.\n*Over The Edge: An automotive industry on overdrive.\n*FYI: Featuring an in-depth report on consumer trending.\n*Retro Review: A look back at ''MotorWeek'' reviews from past seasons.\n*Eye Spy: Featuring photographic closeups of automobiles.\n*Taking the High Road: Featuring automobiles from the past and present.\n\n==Theme music==\nFrom the show's premiere in 1981 until 1987, ''MotorWeek'''s original theme music was composed by Don Barto. Beginning with the 1987-88 season, Mark Roumelis took over as music composer.\n\n==Sets==\nDuring the first six seasons of ''MotorWeek'', the set looks like a styling studio with cars, drafting tools, and paraphernalia on the wall was used from 1981 to 1987. Beginning with the 1987-88 season, ''MotorWeek'' began taping outdoors rather than in a studio.\n\n==Track==\nFrom 1981 to present day, ''MotorWeek'' has been use the 75-80 Dragway.<ref name=dragway>{{cite web|title=MotorWeek Over The Edge:75-80 Dragway|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9wHC7LwT0U|website=YouTube|publisher=Maryland Public Television}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.motorweek.org/ MotorWeek home page]\n* {{IMDb title|0244912|MotorWeek}}\n\n{{PBSTV}}\n\n[[Category:Automotive television series]]\n[[Category:PBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITC Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:1981 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "Winhelper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisodes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MotorWeek"}
{"title_page": "Maroua Brahmi", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| image           =\n| alt             = \n| birth_name      = Maroua Brahmi\n| native_name     = \u0645\u0631\u0648\u0649 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0645\u064a\n| native_name_lang = [[Arabic|Tunisian]]\n| other_names     = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1988|09|19}} \n| birth_place     = [[Gafsa]], [[Tunisia]] \n| residence       = [[Gafsa]], [[Tunisia]] \n| height          = 1.65m \n| weight          = 50kg\n|disability       = [[Cerebral palsy]]\n|disability_class= F32\n|club             =\tTunisian Federation of Sports for the Disabled: Gafsa, TUN\n|coach            = Mohammed Yahya\n| years_active    = 2009\u20132019 ([[Track and field]] F32)\n| university      = \n| medaltemplates  =\n{{MedalSport|Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{TUN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's club throw|Women's club throw F31/32/51]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Women's Shot Put - F32/33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's club throw|Women's club throw F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Women's Shot Put - F32]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]] | [[Club throw]] F31/32/51}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw F31/32/51]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships|2019 Dubai]]|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw F32]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2017 World ParaAthletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World ParaAthletics Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw - F32]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Maroua Brahmi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0631\u0648\u0649 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0645\u064a}}, born September 19, 1988) is a [[Paralympic]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Tunisia]] competing mainly in category F32 throwing events. She is the 2016 Paralympic Champion in [[club throw]] category F32 and the F32 [[shot put]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Maroua Ibrahmi - Bio|url=https://www.paralympic.org/athletics/athletes/biographies|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\nImpaired with [[cerebral palsy]], Brahmi took to sport in 2008,<ref name=\"bio\" /> she made her international debut in 2009,<ref name=\"bio\" /> her first major international competition was at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] held in [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]], where she won a gold medal in the F31/F32/F51 [[club throw]],<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1101/S00182/ipc-athletics-world-champs-off-to-record-breaking-start.htm|website=scoop.co.nz|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> she also came 11th in the F32/F34 [[shot put]].<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nBrahmi competed in the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in [[London]], [[UK]]. There she won a gold medal in Women's club throw F31/32/51 and a bronze medal in the Women's shot put F32/33/34.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/disability-sport/19082588|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Lyon]], [[France]], on winning the gold medal in the [[club throw]] she broke the world record when throwing 24.15 meters,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lyon 2013 - Day five evening review|url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/lyon-2013-day-five-evening-review|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> she also finished 4th in the [[shot put]].<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]], she won gold again in the [[club throw]]<ref name=\"bio\" /> she actually only beat [[Algeria]]n thrower [[Mounia Gasmi]] by 4 centimeters<ref>{{cite web|title=Doha 2015 Results|url=https://www.paralympic.org/doha-2015/schedule-results|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> and she followed that with the gold medal in the F32 [[shot put]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Doha 2015 Results|url=https://www.paralympic.org/doha-2015/schedule-results|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe also managed to win two gold medals at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], firstly winning the F32 [[club throw]] in a new world record distance of 26.93 meters, and again beating [[Mounia Gasmi]] who had to settle for silver medal again,<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's Club Throw F32|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athletics-standings-at-womens-club-throw-f31-32|website=rio2016.com|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> then eight days later she won the F32 [[shot put]] throwing 5.76 meters<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's shot put -F32|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athletics-standings-at-womens-shot-put-f32|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> which was a new Paralympic record, her nearest opponent was over a meter behind.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paralympic shot put records|url=https://db.ipc-services.org/sdms/web/record/at/pdf/type/PR/category/out/gender/W/evt/SHO|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n* Women's Club Throw - F31/32/51\n* Women's Shot Put - F32/33/34\n* Women's Club throw F32\n* Women's Shot put F32\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|maroua-ibrahmi|Maroua Ibrahmi|old_id=904051}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brahmi, Maroua}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Tunisian female athletes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| image           =\n| alt             = \n| birth_name      = Maroua Brahmi\n| native_name     = \u0645\u0631\u0648\u0649 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0645\u064a\n| native_name_lang = [[Arabic|Tunisian]]\n| other_names     = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1988|09|19}} \n| birth_place     = [[Gafsa]], [[Tunisia]] \n| residence       = [[Gafsa]], [[Tunisia]] \n| height          = 1.65m \n| weight          = 50kg\n|disability       = [[Cerebral palsy]]\n|disability_class= F32\n|club             =\tTunisian Federation of Sports for the Disabled: Gafsa, TUN\n|coach            = Mohammed Yahya\n| years_active    = 2009\u20132019 ([[Track and field]] F32)\n| university      = \n| medaltemplates  =\n{{MedalSport|Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{TUN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's club throw|Women's club throw F31/32/51]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Women's Shot Put - F32/33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's club throw|Women's club throw F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Women's Shot Put - F32]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]] | [[Club throw]] F31/32/51}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw F31/32/51]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F32]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships|2019 Dubai]]|[[2019 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw F32]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2017 World ParaAthletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World ParaAthletics Championships \u2013 Women's club throw|Club throw - F32]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Maroua Brahmi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0631\u0648\u0649 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0645\u064a}}, born September 19, 1988) is a [[Paralympic]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Tunisia]] competing mainly in category F32 throwing events. She is the 2016 Paralympic Champion in [[club throw]] category F32 and the F32 [[shot put]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Maroua Ibrahmi - Bio|url=https://www.paralympic.org/athletics/athletes/biographies|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\nImpaired with [[cerebral palsy]], Brahmi took to sport in 2008,<ref name=\"bio\" /> she made her international debut in 2009,<ref name=\"bio\" /> her first major international competition was at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] held in [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]], where she won a gold medal in the F31/F32/F51 [[club throw]],<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1101/S00182/ipc-athletics-world-champs-off-to-record-breaking-start.htm|website=scoop.co.nz|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> she also came 11th in the F32/F34 [[shot put]].<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nBrahmi competed in the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in [[London]], [[UK]]. There she won a gold medal in Women's club throw F31/32/51 and a bronze medal in the Women's shot put F32/33/34.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/disability-sport/19082588|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Lyon]], [[France]], on winning the gold medal in the [[club throw]] she broke the world record when throwing 24.15 meters,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lyon 2013 - Day five evening review|url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/lyon-2013-day-five-evening-review|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> she also finished 4th in the [[shot put]].<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]], she won gold again in the [[club throw]]<ref name=\"bio\" /> she actually only beat [[Algeria]]n thrower [[Mounia Gasmi]] by 4 centimeters<ref>{{cite web|title=Doha 2015 Results|url=https://www.paralympic.org/doha-2015/schedule-results|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> and she followed that with the gold medal in the F32 [[shot put]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Doha 2015 Results|url=https://www.paralympic.org/doha-2015/schedule-results|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe also managed to win two gold medals at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], firstly winning the F32 [[club throw]] in a new world record distance of 26.93 meters, and again beating [[Mounia Gasmi]] who had to settle for silver medal again,<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's Club Throw F32|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athletics-standings-at-womens-club-throw-f31-32|website=rio2016.com|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> then eight days later she won the F32 [[shot put]] throwing 5.76 meters<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's shot put -F32|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athletics-standings-at-womens-shot-put-f32|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> which was a new Paralympic record, her nearest opponent was over a meter behind.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paralympic shot put records|url=https://db.ipc-services.org/sdms/web/record/at/pdf/type/PR/category/out/gender/W/evt/SHO|website=paralympic.org|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n* Women's Club Throw - F31/32/51\n* Women's Shot Put - F32/33/34\n* Women's Club throw F32\n* Women's Shot put F32\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|904051}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brahmi, Maroua}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Tunisian female athletes]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maroua_Brahmi"}
