{"title_page": "Evangelos Venetis", "text_new": "[[File:VenetisASP.jpg|thumb]]\n== Evangelos Venetis ==\nEvangelos Venetis (Greek: \u0395\u03c5\u03ac\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03b5\u03bd\u03ad\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2) (born in 1977 in Athens, Greece) is the coordinator of the Middle East Research Program of the Hellenic Foundation for European and Foreign Policy (ELIAMEP) and a specialist in migration and Islam at the Stavros Niarchos Center for Hellenic Studies in Simon Fraser University in Vancouver, Canada.\n\nHe studied history (1999) and postgraduate studies in the same field at the University of Ioannina (2001). He received his Ph.D. in Islamic and Middle Eastern Studies from the University of Edinburgh, UK (2006). He taught Islamic and Middle Eastern studies as a lecturer for four years at the Arabic, Persian, and Turkish Department at the University of Leiden, the Netherlands. His research interests refer to the Islamic world, migration and the Greek diaspora in the Middle East. He has written books and articles on various topics of the Middle East in the modern and medieval period.\n\nHe is the Director of the Society for Hellenic and Iranian Studies.\n\nHis publications include the following titles: The Persian Alexander: An Annotated Translation (London, IB Tauris, 2018); along with Dr M.S. Alinia, the first Greek-Persian and Persian-Greek dictionary (Athens, 2017,) Greeks in Modern Iran, English translation (Poreia Publications, Athens: 2015); Dr. Saleh Jallad's, The Pedagogy of Arab Leadership (Athens, 2017).\n\n\n\n=== See also ===\n\n\u2022 Islamic and Middle Eastern Studies\n\n\u2022 Hellenic-Iranian Studies\n\n\u2022 Greek Diaspora in the Middle East\n\n\u2022 Iranology\n\n\n\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:VenetisASP.jpg|thumb]]\n== Evangelos Venetis ==\nEvangelos Venetis (Greek: \u0395\u03c5\u03ac\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03b5\u03bd\u03ad\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2) (born in 1977 in Athens, Greece) is the coordinator of the Middle East Research Program of the Hellenic Foundation for European and Foreign Policy (ELIAMEP) and a specialist in migration and Islam at the Stavros Niarchos Center for Hellenic Studies in Simon Fraser University in Vancouver, Canada.\n\nHe studied history (1999) and postgraduate studies in the same field at the University of Ioannina (2001). He received his Ph.D. in Islamic and Middle Eastern Studies from the University of Edinburgh, UK (2006). He taught Islamic and Middle Eastern studies as a lecturer for four years at the Arabic, Persian, and Turkish Department at the University of Leiden, the Netherlands. His research interests refer to the Islamic world, migration and the Greek diaspora in the Middle East. He has written books and articles on various topics of the Middle East in the modern and medieval period.\n\nHe is the Director of the Society for Hellenic and Iranian Studies.\n\nHis publications include the following titles: The Persian Alexander: An Annotated Translation (London, IB Tauris, 2018); along with Dr M.S. Alinia, the first Greek-Persian and Persian-Greek dictionary (Athens, 2017,) Greeks in Modern Iran, English translation (Poreia Publications, Athens: 2015); Dr. Saleh Jallad's, The Pedagogy of Arab Leadership (Athens, 2017).\n\n\n\n=== See also ===\n\n\u2022 Islamic and Middle Eastern Studies\n\n\u2022 Hellenic-Iranian Studies\n\n\u2022 Greek Diaspora in the Middle East\n\n\u2022 Iranology\n\n\n\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added {{Improve categories}} tag to article (UsingTwinkle)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evangelos_Venetis"}
{"title_page": "Nassfeld", "text_new": "{{short description|Town and ski resort in Austria}}\n{{Infobox ski area\n|name= Nassfeld\n|logo= \n|picture= \n|caption= \n|location= Nassfeld, [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]], [[Austria]]\n|nearest_city= [[Hermagor-Pressegger See|Hermagor]]\n|top_elevation= {{convert|2000|m|ft|sp=us}}\n|base_elevation= {{convert|600|m|ft|sp=us}}\n|skiable_area= 110 Piste Kilometers\n|number_trails= \n|longest_run= Carnia, 7.6 km \n|liftsystem= 30 total\n|terrainparks=2, including 1 half pipe\n|snowfall= \n|external_link= {{URL|http://www.nassfeld.at}}\n|}}\n\n[[Image:Nassfeld.jpg|thumb|right|300px|A view at the ski resort from Cube hotel in summer]]\n'''Nassfeld''' or '''Na\u00dffeld''' ({{lang-sl|Mokrine}}, {{lang-it|Passo di Pramollo}}) is a town and [[ski resort]] in the district [[Hermagor-Pressegger See|Hermagor]] of the [[Austria]]n state of [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]].\n\nIt is located below the [[Nassfeld Pass]]. [[Lake Pressegg]] is nearby, where it is possible to swim in summer and [[ice skating|ice skate]] in the winter.\n\n== Ski resort ==\n\n[[File:Resort.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Nassfeld ski resort]]\nNassfeld is a popular sport destination for winter and summer sports which include [[skiing]], [[snowboarding]], [[cross-country skiing]], mountain [[hiking]] and offers more than 1000&nbsp;km of hiking trails. The area has 30 ski lifts: 5 Gondolas, 4 Six-Seater Chairlifts, 4 four-seater chairlifts and 17 tow lifts. The ski resort has over 220 snow machines for creating artificial snow and 110&nbsp;km of ski tracks. The [[Aerial lift|cable car]] called Millennium-Express can lift people to the summit 1919 meters high in less than 15 minutes. The ski resort expands on elevation between 600 and 2000 meters. It has one of Carinthia's longest runs, Carnia, with 7.6 Kilometers in length. weather often differs in these areas but its overall sunny in the summer months and quite a high temperature (5-15 degrees Celsius)\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nassfeld.at/en/}}\n* [http://www.skiresorts-test.com/ski-resorts/nassfeld-hermagor.html Test review, webcams, snow and weather conditions for Nasseld]\n\n{{coord|46.5758|N|13.2619|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ski areas and resorts in Austria]]\n[[Category:Geography of Carinthia (state)]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Carinthia (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Hermagor District]]\n\n\n{{Carinthia-geo-stub}}\n{{Austria-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Town and ski resort in Austria}}\n{{Infobox ski area\n|name= Nassfeld\n|logo= \n|picture= \n|caption= \n|location= Nassfeld, [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]], [[Austria]]\n|nearest_city= [[Hermagor-Pressegger See|Hermagor]]\n|top_elevation= {{convert|2000|m|ft|sp=us}}\n|base_elevation= {{convert|600|m|ft|sp=us}}\n|skiable_area= 110 Piste Kilometers\n|number_trails= \n|longest_run= Carnia, 7.6 km \n|liftsystem= 30 total\n|terrainparks=2, including 1 half pipe\n|snowfall= \n|external_link= {{URL|http://www.nassfeld.at}}\n|}}\n\n[[Image:Nassfeld.jpg|thumb|right|300px|A view at the ski resort from Cube hotel in summer]]\n'''Nassfeld''' or '''Na\u00dffeld''' ({{lang-sl|Mokrine}}, {{lang-it|Passo di Pramollo}}) is a town and [[ski resort]] in the district [[Hermagor-Pressegger See|Hermagor]] of the [[Austria]]n state of [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]]. \n\nIt is located below the [[Nassfeld Pass]]. [[Lake Pressegg]] is nearby, where it is possible to swim in summer and [[ice skating|ice skate]] in the winter.\n\n== Ski resort ==\n\n[[File:Resort.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Nassfeld ski resort]]\nNassfeld is a popular sport destination for winter and summer sports which include [[skiing]], [[snowboarding]], [[cross-country skiing]], mountain [[hiking]] and offers more than 1000&nbsp;km of hiking trails. The area has 30 ski lifts: 5 Gondolas, 4 Six-Seater Chairlifts, 4 four-seater chairlifts and 17 tow lifts. The ski resort has over 220 snow machines for creating artificial snow and 110&nbsp;km of ski tracks. The [[Aerial lift|cable car]] called Millennium-Express can lift people to the summit 1919 meters high in less than 15 minutes. The ski resort expands on elevation between 600 and 2000 meters. It has one of Carinthia's longest runs, Carnia, with 7.6 Kilometers in length. weather often differs in these areas but its overall sunny in the summer months and quite a high temperature (5-15 degrees Celsius)\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nassfeld.at/en/}}\n* [http://www.skiresorts-test.com/ski-resorts/nassfeld-hermagor.html Test review, webcams, snow and weather conditions for Nasseld]\n\n{{coord|46.5758|N|13.2619|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Ski areas and resorts in Austria]]\n[[Category:Geography of Carinthia (state)]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Carinthia (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Hermagor District]]\n\n{{Carinthia-geo-stub}}\n{{Austria-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nassfeld"}
